[[ファイル:Tsukiyomi Jinja Kyotanabe Torii.jpg|thumb|250px|{{center|Torii}}]]
'''Tsukiyomi Shrine''' (つきよみじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kyōtanabe|Q816728|WD=Q816728|1=Kyōtanabe}}, {{ill|lt=Kyoto Prefecture|Q120730|WD=Q120730|1=Kyoto Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha great shrine|Q134917288|WD=Q134917288|1=Shikinai Taisha}} and is known as the birthplace of '''{{ill|lt=Hayato-mai|Q55529681|WD=Q55529681|1=Hayato-mai}}'''.

=== History ===
=== Outline ===
According to shrine tradition, when the shrine buildings were moved from Heijō-kyō to Heian-kyō in {{ill|lt=809|Q30671|WD=Q30671|1=809}} (Daidō 4), divine light was seen on Mt. Ōsumi, and building a shrine at this place marks the founding. During the {{ill|lt=Battle of Toba–Fushimi|Q1193959|WD=Q1193959|1=Battle of Toba–Fushimi}}, {{ill|lt=Iwashimizu Hachimangū|Q710098|WD=Q710098|1=Iwashimizu Hachimangū}} was temporarily relocated here to avoid warfare, and sacred treasures were placed in Yakushi Hall.

=== Court rank ===
*{{ill|lt=Ten'an (Japan)|Q1075611|WD=Q1075611|lt=Ten'an|1=Ten'an}} 3 ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}), {{ill|lt=January 27|Q2284|WD=Q2284|1=January 27}}: from Junior Fifth Lower to Senior Fifth Lower (''{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}'') - written as "Kabai Tsukuyomi-no-Kami"
*{{ill|lt=Gangyō|Q747451|WD=Q747451|1=Gangyō}} 6 ({{ill|lt=877|Q23905|WD=Q23905|1=877}}): Junior First Rank (shrine tradition)

=== Hayato-mai ===
[[ファイル:Hyatomai Denshouti.jpg|thumb|150px|{{center|Monument of the birthplace of Hayato-mai}}]]
From a tradition that Ōsumi {{ill|lt=Hayato|Q1151764|WD=Q1151764|1=Hayato people}} from southern {{ill|lt=Kyushu|Q13987|WD=Q13987|1=Kyushu}} migrated to Ōsumi in the {{ill|lt=Nara period|Q189178|WD=Q189178|1=Nara period}}, and that these Ōsumi Hayato dedicated and transmitted Hayato-mai here, this shrine is regarded as the birthplace of Hayato-mai. At the eve of the annual festival on {{ill|lt=October 14|Q2922|WD=Q2922|1=October 14}}, Hayato-mai is still dedicated (designated an intangible folk cultural property of Kyōtanabe City<ref>{{Cite web|和書|title="Tsukiyomi Shrine and Hayato-mai"|url=http://www.kyotanabe.jp/html/kanko/i/tsukiyomi.htm|website=Kyōtanabe City|accessdate=2019-09-20|language=ja|last=Kyōtanabe City}}</ref>).

Also, the place name "Ōsumi" where this shrine is located is thought to derive from "{{ill|lt=Ōsumi Province|Q981002|WD=Q981002|lt=Ōsumi|1=Ōsumi Province}}" in Kyushu<ref>{{Cite web|和書|title=Ōsumi Hayato-mai|url=http://www.kyotanabe.ed.jp/nc24/culture/htdocs/mu6y5636h-117/|website=www.kyotanabe.ed.jp|accessdate=2020-07-03|publisher=Kyōtanabe City Board of Education}}</ref>.

